==Prior to 20th century==
{{History of Burundi}}

* 1885 - Mohamed Bin Khalfan in power in region.<ref name=historique>{{cite web |url=http://www.mairiebujumbura.gov.bi/index.php/historique |language=fr |work=Mairiebujumbura.gov.bi |title=Historique |publisher= Mairie de Bujumbura |accessdate= 1 September 2017 }}</ref>
* 1899 - Germans establish military settlement at village of Usumbura in colonial [[German East Africa]].{{sfn|Zeleza|2003}}

==20th century==
[[File:1991 map Bujumbura Burundi.jpg|thumb|right|Map of Bujumbura, 1991]]
* 1912 - Usumbura becomes capital of [[Ruanda-Urundi]].<ref name=historique />
* 1916 - Belgians in power in Ruanda-Urundi.<ref name=historique />
* 1928 - Buyenzi neighborhood created.<ref name=historique />
* 1932 - Kabondo neighborhood created.<ref name=historique />
* 1941 - Kabondo neighborhood razed due to poor public health.<ref name=historique />
* 1945 - Kamenge and Kinama neighborhoods created.<ref name=Muni2009 />
* 1952 - [[Bujumbura International Airport|Bujumbura Airport]] opens.
* 1955 - [[Holy Spirit Lycée]] (school) active.
* 1959 - [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Bujumbura|Roman Catholic diocese of Usumbura]] established.<ref>{{cite web |title=Chronology of Catholic Dioceses: Burundi |url= http://www.katolsk.no/organisasjon/verden/chronology/burundi |publisher=[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Oslo]] |location=Norway |accessdate= 31 August 2017 }}</ref>
* 1960
** [[University of Burundi]] founded.{{sfn|Zeleza|2003}}
** [[Burundi National Radio and Television|Radio nationale]] begins broadcasting.
* 1962
** City becomes national capital of newly formed Burundi; Usumbura renamed "Bujumbura."{{sfn|Cybriwsky|2013}}
** Gérard Kibinakanwa becomes mayor.<ref name=mayor2009>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090206051302/http://www.villedebujumbura.org/spip.php?article48 |url=http://www.villedebujumbura.org:80/spip.php?article48 |deadurl=yes |language=fr |title=Succession à la tête de la Mairie de Bujumbura |work=Villedebujumbura.org |publisher=Mairie de Bujumbura |archivedate=6 February 2009 |df= }}</ref>
* 1963
** {{illm|Cibitoke (Bujumbura)|it|lt=Cibitoke}} neighborhood created.<ref name=historique />
** [[Maniema FC]] (football club) formed.
* 1965 - [[École Belge de Bujumbura]] (school) opens.
* 1970 - Population: 78,810 (urban agglomeration).<ref>{{cite book |url= https://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/products/dyb/1980_round.htm |title=Demographic Yearbook 1980 |year= |author=[[United Nations Department of Economic and Social Affairs]], Statistical Office |location=New York |chapter=Population of capital cities and cities of 100,000 and more inhabitants |pages=225-252 }}</ref>
* 1978 - ''Renouveau du Burundi'' government [[Media of Burundi|newspaper]] begins publication.<ref name=europa2004>{{cite book |title=Africa South of the Sahara 2004 |series=Regional Surveys of the World |publisher= [[Europa Publications]] |isbn= 1857431839 |chapter= Burundi |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=jj4J-AXGDaQC |year=2004 }}</ref>
* 1984 - [[Burundi National Radio and Television|Télévision nationale]] begins broadcasting.
* 1990 - Population: 235,440.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/products/dyb/dyb2005.htm |work=Demographic Yearbook 2005 |year= |publisher=[[United Nations Statistics Division]] |title= Population of capital cities and cities of 100,000 or more inhabitants }}</ref>
* 1991 - [[Kamenge Youth Centre]] established.
* 1995
** Ethnic violence during the [[Burundian Civil War]].<ref name=bbc>{{cite web |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-13087604 |accessdate= 31 August 2017 |title= Burundi Profile: Timeline |work= [[BBC News]] }}</ref><ref name=europa2001>{{cite book|publisher=Europa Publications |title=Political Chronology of Africa |series=Political Chronologies of the World |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=0O86sZdHfHUC |isbn=0203409957 |year= 2001 |chapter= Burundi |page= 51+ }}</ref>
** 11 March: Government official [[Ernest Kabushemeye]] killed.
* 1996
** Army-rebel (Tutsi-Hutu) conflict, especially in {{illm|Kamenge|fr}}.{{sfn|Young|2010}}
** {{illm|Radio Umwizero|fr}} begins broadcasting.<ref name=europa2004 />
* 1998 - Civilians killed by Hutu rebels at airport.{{sfn|Young|2010}}
* 2000
** 13 October: Army-rebel (Tutsi-Hutu) conflict occurs near city.<ref name=europa2001 />
** 31 December: Civilians killed by Hutu rebels near city.<ref name=europa2001 />

==21st century==
[[File:Bujumbura 29.36607E 3.37443S.jpg|thumb|right|Satellite view of Bujumbura, 2005]]
* 2003
** City besieged by rebel forces.<ref name=bbc />
** April: Peacekeeping [[African Union Mission in Burundi]] headquartered in city.
* 2005 - City administration divided into 13 [[Bujumbura_Mairie_Province#Administrative_subdivisions|neighborhoods]]: Buterere, [[Commune of Buyenzi|Buyenzi]], {{illm|Bwiza|fr}}, {{illm|Cibitoke (Bujumbura)|it|lt=Cibitoke}}, Gihosha, Kamenge, Kanyosha, [[Commune of Kinama|Kinama]], Kinindo, Musaga, Ngagara, {{illm|Nyakabiga|fr}}, and {{illm|Rohero|sv|Commune of Rohero}}. Each has its own council and leader.<ref name=Muni2009>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090206051231/http://www.villedebujumbura.org/spip.php?article3 |url=http://www.villedebujumbura.org/spip.php?article3 |deadurl=yes |language=fr |title=L’administration de la Municipalité de Bujumbura |work=Villedebujumbura.org |publisher=Mairie de Bujumbura |archivedate= 6 February 2009 }}</ref>
* 2007 - September: Conflict between factions of the [[National Forces of Liberation]].<ref name=bbc />
* 2008 - Population: 497,169.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/products/dyb/dyb2015.htm |work=Demographic Yearbook 2015 |year=2016 |publisher=United Nations Statistics Division |title= Population of capital cities and cities of 100,000 or more inhabitants }}</ref>
* 2011 - 30 November: [[East African Community]] summit held in city.<ref>{{cite book|editor=Andreas Mehler|title=Africa Yearbook: Politics, Economy and Society South of the Sahara in 2011 |year= 2012 |volume=8 |publisher=Koninklijke Brill |isbn=978-90-04-24178-7 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TSUzAQAAQBAJ |display-editors=etal}}</ref>
* 2012
** March: Labor strike.<ref>{{cite book|editor=Andreas Mehler |title=Africa Yearbook: Politics, Economy and Society South of the Sahara in 2012 |year= 2013 |volume=9 |publisher=Koninklijke Brill |isbn=978-90-04-25600-2 |chapter=Burundi |author= Stef Vandeginste |pages= 291-300 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=Af9AAQAAQBAJ |display-editors=etal}}</ref>
** Saidi Juma becomes [[List of current provincial governors in Burundi|mayor]].
* 2013 - Central market burns down.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.rfi.fr/afrique/20130127-burundi-vaste-incendie-marche-central-bujumbura |work=Rfi.fr |title=Burundi: vaste incendie au marché central de Bujumbura |language=fr |date=27 January 2013 }}</ref>
* 2015 - [[Burundian unrest (2015–present)]].

